23 182 :M
f1_12 sf
.198 .02(This proposal is for an editorial change in the description of the Standard C++ library.  The contents are)J
23 194 :M
.182 .018(much the same as the Working Paper, but the sections have been re-arranged and important information)J
23 206 :M
-.021(has been added.)A
23 230 :M
.326 .033(This proposal addresses many of the small editorial issues \(\322boxes\323\) that were raised during the review)J
23 242 :M
1.165 .116(of the San Diego rewrite of Clause 17.  Strictly speaking, editorial proposals do not require formal)J
23 254 :M
.827 .083(proposals, motions, and votes.  However, the changes proposed are widespread enough to warrant an)J
23 266 :M
-.02(explicit proposal and discussion.)A
23 292 :M
f4_14 sf
-.672(2.)A
59 292 :M
-.128(Proposal)A
23 316 :M
f1_12 sf
.068 .007(Re-arrange the material in \24417.1, \322Introduction\323 \(_lib.introduction_\), as shown in the attached document)J
23 328 :M
-.033(labeled 17, Library.)A
23 352 :M
3.134 .313(Move some of the material on differences from the C library to Annex C, \322Compatibility\323)J
23 364 :M
-.003(\(_diff.library_\), as shown in the attached document labeled 18, Compatibility.)A
23 390 :M
f4_14 sf
-.672(3.)A
59 390 :M
-.075(Discussion)A
23 414 :M
f1_12 sf
.525 .052(The San Diego rewrite of Clause 17 imported far more of the Stnadard C library than the Library WG)J
23 426 :M
.571 .057(ever intended with proposal 92\3200024/N0101, \322ISO C Library Inclusion,\323 as voted on and approved at)J
23 438 :M
.116 .012(the London meeting in March, 1992.  Basically, the rewrite defines its terms using the vocabulary of the)J
23 450 :M
.015 .001(C standard, defines the C++ library as an extension of the C library, specifies the C++ library in terms of)J
23 462 :M
.499 .05(C library facilities, and uses the same functional style as the C standard to document the classes in the)J
23 474 :M
-.047(C++ library.)A
23 498 :M
.192 .019(On a strictly technical basis, the rewrite might be considered an adequate specification for the Standard.)J
23 510 :M
1.377 .138(However, when taken together, the results are inappropriate for C++ and inadequate as a Standard)J
23 522 :M
1.531 .153(reference:  necessary information is hard to find, important constraints are documented obscurely,)J
23 534 :M
.197 .02(important features of C++ are ignored or underutilized, and some aspects of the library are substantially)J
23 546 :M
-.048(overspecified.)A
23 570 :M
.932 .093(The advantages of the San Diego rewrite include an exhaustive treatment of the library\325s contents, a)J
23 582 :M
-.012(consistent organization, and wording in terms of accepted \322standardese.\323)A
23 606 :M
.685 .069(This proposal attempts to keep the advantages of the San Diego rewrite, while eliminating most of its)J
23 618 :M
-.003(disadvantages.  The new version balances several competing demands:)A
95 630 :M
(\245  a comprehensive, yet understandable, framework for organizing the library)S
95 642 :M
-.015(\245  reuse of C library terms and concepts, )A
f2_12 sf
-.018(as appropriate to C++)A
95 654 :M
f1_12 sf
-.001(\245  exhaustive summary of the library\325s contents, organized alphabetically)A
95 666 :M
-.01(\245  a useful reference to the library\325s contents, organized by concept)A
23 690 :M
1.154 .115(Perhaps the most important advantage of the proposed new version is that it provides an integrated)J
23 702 :M
(description of the entire C++ library, including the features incorporated from the C standard.)S
endp
